  "datePublished": "2026-03-20",
  "description": "A HohfeldianPosition is one of eight fundamental legal concepts organized in two quartets — (claim, duty, privilege, no-claim) and (power, liability, immunity, disability) — that together constitute the primitive vocabulary for any normative system. Every normative relation between two parties can be decomposed into one or more Hohfeldian positions. The fundamental distinction: first-quartet positions govern what parties must, may, and cannot do (act-level); second-quartet positions govern who can alter act-level normative relations (meta-level).",
